# Public Prosecutor _v_ Mohamed Selim Bin M H Arkatti  

### \[2022\] SGDC 82

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">Traffic Police Summons 000449-2021, Magistrate's Appeal No 9064-2022-01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">18 April 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Salina Bte Ishak</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Lim Hian Teck (Criminal Investigation Department) for the Prosecution; The accused acting in person.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Mohamed Selim Bin M H Arkatti</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9064/2022/01.\]

18 April 2022

### District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

## Background

1       The accused, Mr Mohamed Selim Bin M H Arkatti, a 55 years-old male Singapore citizen had faced the following charge:

Charge

> are charged that on 8 September 2021 at or about 12.04 p.m., along Lavender Street junction of Serangoon Road, Singapore, did drive a motor vehicle SDM808X on a road in a manner which is dangerous to the public, having regard to all the circumstances of the case, including the nature, condition and use of the road, and the amount of traffic which is actually at the time, or which might reasonably be expected to be, on the road, to wit, by failing to conform to red-light signal along Serangoon Road towards the direction of Central Expressway and collided onto one pedestrian who was crossing at the pedestrian crossing on traffic green man from your right to left perspective, and hurt was caused to one Ho Tuck Wai/Male/45 by such driving, you have thereby committed an offence under Section 64(1) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276.

> And further that you, before the commission of the said offence, were convicted on 27 June 1997 in Subordinate Court No. 23N, for an offence of Speeding (1-20KMPH) under Section 63(4) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276 vide Report Number S96061883XD, which conviction has not been set aside, and you are therefore liable to be punished under Section 64(2B)(b) of the same Act.

2       On 29 March 2022, the accused pleaded guilty to the charge and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification. After carefully considering the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence and the accused’s plea in mitigation, I sentenced the accused to fine of $5,000 in default 15 days’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of 18 months with effect from 29 March 2022.

3       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed his Notice of Appeal against the order of disqualification on 31 March 2022. He has paid the fine in full.

4       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

## Salient Facts

#### Involved Party

5       The accused was the driver of the motorcar, SDM808X, at the time of the accident.

6       The victim is Ho Tuck Wai, Male, Chinese, Singaporean, 45 years old. He was the pedestrian, at the time of the accident.

7       The witness is Chew Heng Wee, Male, Chinese, Singaporean, 46 years old. He was the driver of one motorcar which was stationary at the junction due to red light at the time of the accident.

#### First Incident Report

8       On 8 September 2021 at or about 12.04pm, the Police received information stating: “CAME ACROSS CASE OF RTA” FIR caller was A1R4B, who did not witness the accident. The accident was reported along Serangoon Road junction of Lavender Street.

#### Facts of Case

9       On 8 September 2021 at or about 12.04pm, along Serangoon Road junction of Lavender Street, Singapore, the accused was driving motorcar, SDM808X on a road in a manner which is dangerous to the public, having regard to all the circumstances of the case, including the nature, condition and use of the road, and the amount of traffic which is actually at the time, or which might reasonably be expected to be, on the road, by failing to conform to red-light when driving across the junction and had collided onto a pedestrian, who was crossing at the designated pedestrian crossing on traffic green man, from the accused’s right to left perspective and hurt was caused to the victim.

#### Footage

10     Footage from the witness’s in-car camera revealed that the witness was stationary along Balestier Road towards Lavender Street junction of Serangoon Road, with traffic light showing red only. Few seconds after the traffic light turned green for the witness’s direction, the accused was seen driving across the junction from the witness’s right to left perspective. As the accused was driving through the junction, the victim, who was on the witness’s left side perspective, started to jog across the road. As such, the accused’s front portion collided onto the victim’s left side.

![](data:image;base64,)

#### Damages

11     There was no fresh damages on the accused’s motorcar as shown in the vehicle damage report.

#### Injury

12     The victim was conveyed to Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH) by ambulance, conscious. The medical report revealed that the victim sustained mild tenderness over the left shoulder and left knee, plus a left parietal scalp laceration. The victim was hospitalised for one day from 8 September 2021 to 9 September 2021 and given four days of hospitalisation leave from 8 September 2021 to 11 September 2021.

#### Prevailing Condition

13     At the time of accident, the weather was clear, road surface was dry and traffic volume was moderate.

## Sentencing

### Prescribed Penalty

14     The prescribed penalty for an offence of dangerous driving by a repeat offender under s 64(1) punishable under s 64(2B)(_b_) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”) is fine not exceeding $20,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 4 years or to both. Pursuant to s 64(3) of the RTA, a person is regarded as repeat offender under subsections 2(_b_), (2A)(_b_), (2B)(_b_) and (2C)(_b_) respectively if the person has been convicted for an offence under ss 63, 65 or 116 of the RTA.

15     In addition, s 42(1) of the RTA provides that a court before which person convicted of an offence in connection with the driving of a motor vehicle, may where so required by this Act, order him to be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for life or for such period as the court may think fit.

## Antecedents

16     On 26 June 1997 in Court 23N, the accused was convicted for an offence of speeding under s 63(1) of the RTA where a fine of $400 was imposed.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

17     The Prosecution had submitted that this was a low culpability case and there were no culpability-enhancing factors such as speeding involved. In respect of the harm, based on the injury sustained and the low number of days of medical leave it was further submitted that this was a low harm case. However, the Prosecution had taken into consideration his speeding antecedent. As it was a low culpability and a low harm case, the Prosecution had sought a fine of $5,000 to $6,000 and disqualification for a period of two years for all classes of vehicles.

## Mitigation

18     In his oral plea in mitigation, the accused had asked for a lower sentence. He highlighted that his earlier charge mentioned in consideration was in 1997 which was almost 30 years ago. The accused submitted that he was distracted on the day of the offence. According to him, it was an accident and that he did not intend to cause harm to the victim.

19     He further submitted that he had stopped vehicle and rendered immediate help to the victim without due care to himself. There was blood all over his hand as he tried to stop the bleeding from the victim’s head. He had asked the victim if he was alright. He had also tried to visit the victim but was told by Investigating Officer that it was not allowed.

## Prosecution’s Reply

20     In response to the plea in mitigation, the Prosecution submitted that while the antecedent may be dated, it was still relevant for the court to consider in sentencing. It was further submitted that under the Road Traffic (Pedestrian Crossing) Rules (1990, Rev. Ed.), the accused is supposed to slow down when approaching the crossing but had failed to do so.

## Decision on sentence

### Sentencing approach

21     S 64(1) of the RTA encapsulates the primary offence of reckless or dangerous driving on a road. The subsequent subsections from ss 64(2), 64(2A) and 64(2B) are the penalty prescribing provisions, each tiered according to the degree of hurt caused and for s 64(2C), for any other case of non-personal injury or potential harm. For ease of reference, I have set out the relevant provisions below:

![](data:image;base64,)

![](data:image;base64,)

22     The 2019 amendments to s 64(1) of the RTA resulted in a tiered approach in the prescribed penalties where a first offender under s 64(1) who fell at the lowest end of the spectrum of no personal injury or potential harm is occasioned is liable to a fine not exceeding $5,000 or to imprisonment not exceeding 12 months or to both. At the highest end of the spectrum where death is caused, the first offender is liable to imprisonment of not less than two years and not more than eight years imprisonment. In addition, enhanced penalties as well as minimum disqualification periods were introduced for offences where death or grievous hurt is caused as well as for a repeat offender, a serious offender as well as a serious repeat offender.

#### Irresponsible driving under the Road Traffic Act

23     The prescribed penalty for the present offence under s 64(1) of the RTA was enhanced on 1 November 2019 following the passing of the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019). The Amendment Act arose out of a review of the RTA and it aimed to provide stronger deterrence against irresponsible driving, according to the explanation presented by the Second Minister for Home Affairs, Mrs Josephine Teo (the “Minister”) to Parliament on 8 July 2019 (_Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report_ (8 July 2019), vol 94). The Minister’s explanation is set out below:

> I will start with our enhanced approach towards irresponsible driving offences. Today, irresponsible driving offences are prosecuted in two ways. One way is under the Penal Code, for Rash Act and Negligent Act. Another way is under the RTA, for Reckless or Dangerous Driving, and Driving without Due Care or Reasonable Consideration. The penalties differ.

> For better clarity and consistency, we propose to consolidate irresponsible driving offences under the RTA. We will also streamline the offences into two classes: the first category is Reckless or Dangerous Driving, which I will refer to as Dangerous Driving in the rest of the speech. The second category is Driving without Due Care or Reasonable Consideration, which I will refer to as Careless Driving. 

> The definitions of Dangerous Driving and Careless Driving are currently in the RTA. We will maintain the current definitions.

> Dangerous Driving is more serious than Careless Driving. The two can be differentiated, on a case-by-case basis. The three main considerations, among others, are as follows.

> First, whether the manner of driving predictably puts other road users at risk and cause other road users to be unable to react in time. Examples of driving that are considered as dangerous, as opposed to careless, include swerving across lanes suddenly and without warning, driving against the flow of traffic and speeding.

> Second, whether the motorist had driven, even though he should have known he was not in a condition to drive safely. Examples of behaviour that are considered dangerous include using mobile devices while driving and failing to use visual aids such as spectacles even though he is seriously short-sighted.

> Third, whether the road situation required the motorist to take extra care but he did not. Examples include when he is approaching a zebra crossing, or a junction where other road users have the right of way.

> When determining the punishment, we will look at the circumstances under which the offence is committed. The threshold for Dangerous Driving is higher than Careless Driving; so too the penalties. 

> Besides looking at the circumstances of the offence, our enhanced approach will also consider the level of harm caused. If the motorist causes more harm, the level of punishment will be higher. 

> There will be four levels of harm: Death, Grievous Hurt, Hurt and Endangering Life. Such tiering of harm is not new in our laws – the Penal Code already has it. 

> To summarise, we will enhance our overall approach to penalise irresponsible driving depending on: (a) the circumstances of the offence – whether it constitutes Dangerous Driving or Careless Driving; and (b) the level of harm caused – whether they result in Death, Grievous Hurt, Hurt, or Endangering Life. 

24     As at the date of my decision, there is no existing sentencing framework enunciated by the High Court for offences under s 64(1), particularly for an offence punishable under s 64(2B)(_b_) of the RTA. Although the present appeal is only against the disqualification order, for completeness I will explain the reasons for the sentence that I had imposed.

25     In the recent case of _Wu Zhi Yong v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 261</span>(“_Wu Zhi Yong_”), Menon CJ had prescribed a sentencing framework for an offence reckless driving under s 64(1) punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) read with s 64(2C)(_c_) of the RTA. The prescribed penalty for an offence punishable under section 64(2C)(_a_) of the RTA is fine not exceeding $5,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or to both. Where the offence involves a serious offender, he is liable to a fine of not less than $2,000 and not more than $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or to both, in addition to the punishment under section 64(2C)(a) of the RTA.

26     Although the present case concerns a repeat offender for an offence of dangerous driving under s 64(1) of the RTA, I was of the view the observations as well as the sentencing approach set out by Menon CJ provides some useful guidance on how an offence under s 64(2B)(_b_) of the RTA should be dealt with.

27     In _Wu Zhi Yong_, after a careful consideration of different sentencing approaches at \[22\] to \[29\], Menon CJ had prescribed the sentencing band approach when dealing with offences punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) read with ss 64(2C)(_c_) of the RTA. At \[30\] and \[48\] of his judgment, Menon CJ had set out the following sentencing approach:

> _The sentencing approach_

> 30 At the first step, as set out in _Terence Ng_ at \[39\], the court should identify the band applicable to the offence and the indicative starting point with reference to that band, having regard to the _offence_\-specific factors present. These would encompass factors relating to the manner and mode by which the offence was committed, as well as the harm caused by the offender. At the second step, the court would have regard to the _offender_\-specific factors, being the aggravating and mitigating factors that are personal to the offender...

> 48 At the second step of the analysis, the court will have regard to the offender-specific factors. Examples of these factors have been set out at \[62\] – \[71\] of _Terence Ng_ and apply equally in the present framework. Offender-specific aggravating factors include offences taken into consideration for the purposes of sentencing, the presence of relevant antecedents (apart from where the offender’s antecedents have been taken into account under the “repeat offender” or “serious repeat offender” provisions), and evidence showing a lack of remorse. Offender-specific mitigating factors include evidence of genuine remorse and an offender’s youth.

28     The sentencing band prescribed in _Wu Zhi Yong_ is set out below:

#### Offence-specific factors

29     In my view, a sentencing band approach would similarly be the appropriate sentencing approach for the present offence with the necessary upward calibration made to the range of sentences in each band in order to utilise the full range of the statutory penalties. I was mindful that for an offence under s 64(1) punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) read with s 64(2C)(_c_) of the RTA, the maximum sentence is $15,000 or two years’ imprisonment or to both whereas the maximum sentences for an offence punishable under s 64(2B)(_b_) of the RTA is $20,000 or four years’ imprisonment or to both.

30     Hence, guided by the sentencing approach as set out in _Wu Zhi Yong_, I first considered the offence-specific factors to determine the appropriate sentencing band where the present offence should be situated. In my view, some of the offence-specific factors considered by the High Court in _Wu Zhi Yong_ at \[36\] under the sentencing bands would also be relevant in the present case, namely:

> (a)      _Serious potential harm_: Apart from actual harm, it has long been accepted that regard should also be had to the potential harm that can result from the act of dangerous or reckless driving (see _Stansilas Fabian Kester v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 5 SLR 755</span> (“_Stansilas”_) at \[47\]; _Public Prosecutor v Koh Thiam Huat_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 4 SLR 1099</span> (“_Koh Thiam Huat_”) at \[41\]). The level of potential harm would be “assessed against facts which would include … the condition of the road, the volume of traffic or number of pedestrians actually on or which might reasonably be expected to be on the road at the relevant time, the speed and manner of driving, visibility at the relevant time, the type of vehicle, and any particular vulnerabilities (_eg_ a truck or car colliding into a motorcycle or pedestrian)”: _Neo Chuan Sheng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGHC 97</span> at \[22\];

> (b)      _Serious property damage_: The extent of property damage caused is a relevant sentencing factor. As a general rule, the amount of any loss or damage may serve as a proxy indicator of harm;

> (c)      _An offender’s reason or motivation for driving_: The court in _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Suse_”) held that an offender’s reason or motivation for driving could be an aggravating (or conceivably, in some circumstances, even a mitigating) factor in respect of an offence of drink driving. The court further considered that the gravity of an offender’s conduct would be increased if he had, at that time, been driving a passenger for hire or reward (at \[33\]);

> (d)      _Increased culpability_: In _Koh Thiam Huat_ at \[41\], the court considered that factors _increasing_ an accused person’s culpability for an offence of dangerous driving would include a _particularly dangerous manner_ of driving;

> (e)      _The offender’s conduct following the offence or attempt to evade arrest_: Conduct that is “belligerent or violent” upon arrest would constitute an aggravating factor: _Edwin Suse_ at \[32\]. Likewise, the failure to stop in an attempt to evade arrest or to avoid apprehension should also weigh against an offender: _Public Prosecutor v Lee Meng Soon_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 4 SLR(R) 240</span> at \[33\].

> (f)      _the number of victims involved_: Where there are multiple victims impacted by the accused’s dangerous or reckless driving, this would be regarded as an aggravating factor;

> (g)      _the relevant antecedents_: In addition, as the offender is a repeat offender, a factor to consider is whether the previous conviction is under ss 63, 65 or 116 of the RTA, the sentences imposed as well as the number of such antecedents.

#### Proposed sentencing bands

31     The range of sentences that can be imposed for the present offence is a fine not exceeding $20,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding four years or to both.

#### Band 1

32     In my view, an offence with a lower level of seriousness and with no offence-specific aggravating factors, the range of a fine between $3,000 to $20,000 and/or up to three months’ imprisonment and a disqualification period of two to three years for all classes of vehicles can be considered. As the present charge involves a repeat offender for an offence of dangerous driving, I was of the view that the starting point for the fine range should be reflective of the seriousness of the offence. This is an upward calibration from the Band 1 range prescribed in _Wu Zhi Yong_ in view of the higher maximum fine as well as the longer imprisonment term.

#### Band 2

33     For the next band involving a higher level of seriousness with more than one offence-specific aggravating factors, a range of between three months’ imprisonment and up to two years’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period between three to four years can be considered. This is similarly an upward calibration from the Band 2 range prescribed in _Wu Zhi Yong._ The accused’s level of culpability would typically be in the medium range.

#### Band 3

34     The final band would be reserved for the most serious case of causing grievous hurt by reckless or dangerous driving where there are multiple aggravating factors and the offender’s level of culpability is high. For such cases, a range of between two to four years’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period of four to five years would be appropriate. This is also an upward calibration from the Band 3 range prescribed in _Wu Zhi Yong._

#### Calibration of sentence

35     The next step would be for the court to calibrate the sentence after having regard to the offender-specific factors. The relevant factors would include offences that are taken into consideration for the purposes of sentencing, the presence of relevant antecedents and evidence showing a lack of remorse. Offender-specific mitigating factors include a clean record, an early plea of guilt, evidence of genuine remorse and an offender’s youth.

36     I now turn to the facts of the present case.

## Offence-specific factors

#### Manner and mode of offence

37     In the present case, the accused had driven his motorcar in a dangerous manner by failing to conform to a traffic red-light signal along the Serangoon Road junction of Lavender Street and had collided onto the victim who had jogged across the pedestrian crossing when traffic green man signal came on. At the time of the accident, the weather was clear, the road surface was dry and traffic volume was moderate. According to the accused, he had been distracted on the day of the accident.

38     The accident was captured by the witness’s in-car camera as his car was stationary along Balestier Road towards the Lavender Street junction of Serangoon Road due to the red light at the time of the accident. The footage showed the accused’s car travelling across the junction at a constant speed even though a vehicle travelling in the same direction had stopped. As soon as the accused’s car entered the junction, the traffic light turned green in the witness’s favour as well as for vehicles in the opposite direction.

39     When the accused was in the middle of the junction, the victim began crossing the junction and the accused’s vehicle showed no signs of slowing down. The front left portion of the accused’s car then hit the victim as he jogged across causing the latter to be flung onto the road from the impact. From the footage, it appeared that the victim was unaware of the presence of the accused’s motorcar as it travelled across the junction unlike the other pedestrian who managed to step back and avoid being hit by the accused’s motorcar.

40     Based on the above, as the accident arose out of a momentary lapse of concentration and I agreed with the Prosecution that as there was no culpability enhancing factors, I found the accused’s level of culpability to be low.

#### Nature of harm caused

41     I considered the fact that as a pedestrian, the victim was in a vulnerable position from any impact arising from a collision with a motorcar. The victim sustained mild tenderness over the left shoulder and left knee, plus a left parietal scalp laceration. He was hospitalised for one day from 8 September 2021 to 9 September 2021 and given four days of hospitalisation leave from 8 September 2021 to 11 September 2021. In light of the nature of the harm caused, I agreed with Prosecution that degree of harm caused in the present case is low.

#### Serious potential harm

42     I had also considered the potential harm to other road users, namely pedestrians who were in close proximity to the accident, particularly the three other pedestrians who had waited with the victim to cross the pedestrian crossing. Had they also made their way together with the victim once the green man signal came on, they too could have been involved in the accident as a result of the accused’s dangerous driving.

43     Based on the above factors, as there were no culpability enhancing factors present, I was of the view that the present case fell within the lower end of Band 1 where the proposed range is a fine between $3,000 to $20,000 and/or up to three months’ imprisonment and a disqualification period of two to three years for all classes of vehicles can be considered.

44     As this was a road situation which required the accused to take extra care when approaching a signalised junction but he had not, I was of the view as a starting point, a fine higher than the proposed minimum of $3,000 but lower than the mid-point of the maximum fine _ie_ $10,000 and a disqualification for a period of two years as a form of deterrence was necessary. I was also of the view that the custodial threshold had not been crossed.

## Offender-specific factors

#### Mitigating factors

45     The next step was for me to calibrate the sentence after considering offender-specific factors. I gave due weight to the following mitigating factors namely that the accused had pleaded guilty to a single charge, he had stopped his motorcar and rendered immediate help to the victim. He was remorseful for his actions and had attempted to visit the victim after the accident.

46     Apart from his previous conviction for speeding in June 1997, there were no compounded offences in his driving record. Furthermore, this antecedent had already been taken into account under the “repeat offender” provision for the purpose of this charge.

47     The Prosecution had sought a fine of between $5,000 to $6,000 and disqualification for a period of two years for all classes of vehicles. The accused had asked for a lower sentence than that sought by the Prosecution.

48     All things considered, I had calibrated the starting point downwards to a fine of $5,000 and I was of the view that a disqualification order of 18 months disqualification for all classes of vehicles was appropriate after having regard to both the offence-specific and offender-specific factors. I note that the accused has not appealed against the fine of $5000 I had imposed.

49     As there is no prescribed minimum disqualification period for the present charge, s 42(1) of the RTA applies and the court may order him to be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for life or for such period as the court may think fit. In my view, a disqualification for a period of 18 months for all classes of vehicles was necessary as a form of deterrence to address the accused’s poor and irresponsible driving.

50     All things considered, I was of the view that a sentence of $5,000 in default 15 days’ imprisonment and a disqualification from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of 18 months with effect from 29 March 2022 to 28 September 2023 to be just and appropriate in the circumstances.
